erficial temporal artery","Branch of the vertebral artery","Branch of the ascending pharyngeal artery","Branch of the maxillary artery"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emiddle meningeal artery is a branch of the maxillary artery\u003C/strong\u003E that enters the skull through the foramen spinosum. It supplies the dura mater and creates distinctive grooves on the inner surface of the skull.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBranch of the ophthalmic artery\u003C/strong\u003E - The ophthalmic artery gives rise to the anterior meningeal artery via the ethmoidal arteries\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBranch of the vertebral artery\u003C/strong\u003E - The vertebral arteries give meningeal branches to the posterior cranial fossa\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBranch of the superficial temporal artery\u003C/strong\u003E - The superficial temporal artery does not provide meningeal branches\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBranch of the ascending pharyngeal artery\u003C/strong\u003E - While this artery does have small meningeal branches, it is not the origin of the middle meningeal artery\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe middle meningeal artery is clinically significant as it can be damaged in skull fractures, leading to epidural haematoma formation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The middle meningeal artery is a branch of the maxillary artery that enters the skull through the foramen spinosum and supplies the dura mater.","Damage to the middle meningeal artery, often from skull fractures, can cause an epidural haematoma."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","Moore KL, Dalley AF, Agur A. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Lippincott Williams and Wilkins; 2017."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64039"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17334"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64039","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64039"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-12T09:36:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-12T09:37:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10024"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78696"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4904","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4904"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Neuroanatomy","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-13T23:02:33+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-13T23:02:33+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"t